  "prompt": "If black holes pull in all matter due to a high gravitational pull, but light has no mass and also isn't considered matter, how can black holes exist?",
  "response": "Black holes do indeed exert a strong gravitational pull, which affects both matter and light. The confusion often arises from the distinction between mass and energy. While light (photons) does not have mass in the conventional sense (it is massless), it does carry energy and momentum, which allow it to interact with gravitational fields.\n\nAccording to Einstein's theory of general relativity, gravity is not just a force acting on masses, but rather a curvature of spacetime created by mass and energy. This means that anything with energy (including light) is affected by gravity. When light passes near a massive object, it follows the curvature of spacetime, and can be bent or focused, a phenomenon known as gravitational lensing. \n\nIn the case of black holes, their gravitational pull is so strong that within a certain region called the event horizon, the curvature of spacetime becomes so extreme that not even light can escape. This is why they are called \"black holes\"\u2014once anything crosses the event horizon, it cannot return or be observed from the outside.\n\nIn summary, black holes do exist and they can influence light because light, while massless, is still affected by gravity through its energy and the curvature of spacetime.",
